# Copy to .env (under apps/api/) or root. NEVER commit.

DATABASE_URL=postgresql://gw2analytics:gw2analytics@localhost:5432/gw2analytics
S3_ENDPOINT=http://localhost:9000
S3_ACCESS_KEY=gw2analytics
S3_SECRET_KEY=gw2analytics-secret
S3_BUCKET=gw2analytics
SECRET_KEY=change-me-to-a-random-32-byte-hex-string
ENV=dev

# v0.9.1 webhook SSRF defense (plan 005). When unset (default) the
# webhook URL validator blocks any resolved address that targets a
# private/loopback/link-local/multicast range (covers IPv4 RFC1918 +
# 127.0.0.0/8 + 169.254/16 + IPv6 ::1 + fc00::/7 + fe80::/10).
PRODUCTION DEPLOYMENTS MUST KEEP THIS UNSET (= strict).
Set to 1 ONLY in trusted dev environments where the webhook
# subscriber needs to reach an internal endpoint (e.g. a local Redis
# or service-mesh proxy). DO NOT set in production -- a leaked env
# turns the gateway into an SSRF vector against internal services
# (AWS IMDS, internal admin panels, etc.).
# GW2ANALYTICS_ALLOW_PRIVATE_WEBHOOK_URLS=

# v0.10.0 plan 031: webhook secret at rest envelope encryption (Fernet).
# REQUIRED at app startup; the gateway refuses to boot without a
# KEK of exactly 44 chars (URL-safe base64 of 32 random bytes = the
# Fernet key format). Generate via:
#   python -c "from cryptography.fernet import Fernet; print(Fernet.generate_key().decode())"
# Store in a secrets manager (Vault / AWS Secrets Manager / sealed-secrets).
# NEVER commit the real KEK to git.
#
# WARNING: data loss risk. SECRETS_KEK is the SOLE decryption key.
# If it is lost or rotated without running the KEK-rotation migration
# (see the 5-step flow below), ALL existing webhook subscriptions
# will PERMANENTLY fail to dispatch. HMAC signatures will be silently
# wrong on every POST (cryptography.fernet.InvalidToken caught + logged
# but never recovered). Operators MUST:
# 1. Store the KEK in a secrets manager. NEVER commit.
# 2. Test KEK recovery by decrypting a known ciphertext row before
#    relying on the encryption layer in production.

# v0.10.12 plan 015: SECRETS_KEK rotation flow (USE WITH CARE; data
# loss risk if misapplied). After this migration ships, KEK rotation
# is fully in-process + offline; no future v0.10.0+-era enhancement
# is required. The flow supports zero-downtime rotation via the
# ``SECRETS_KEK_FALLBACK`` env list (combines plan 015 + plan 016):
# 1. Generate a fresh KEK:
#    python -c "from cryptography.fernet import Fernet; print(Fernet.generate_key().decode())"
# 2. Copy the EXISTING ``SECRETS_KEK`` value into ``SECRETS_KEK_OLD``
#    AND paste the SAME value into ``SECRETS_KEK_FALLBACK`` (the
#    fallback list keeps read-path operational during the migration
#    window — in-flight decryption still succeeds against rows not
#    yet migrated; both KEKs must be 44-char URL-safe base64 per the
#    validator above).
# 3. Assign the new KEK to ``SECRETS_KEK`` (write-time kicks in
#    immediately — NEW ``POST /api/v1/webhooks`` subscriptions are
#    encrypted under the new KEK from this point onward).
# 4. Run the migration CLI directly:
#      uv run python apps/api/scripts/rotate_kek.py \
#          > rotate_audit.jsonl 2> rotate_summary.log
#    (Lives at ``apps/api/scripts/rotate_kek.py`` — invoked as a
#    standalone CLI, NOT as ``python -m gw2analytics_api.scripts.*``.
#    Reads ``SECRETS_KEK_OLD`` + ``SECRETS_KEK`` from env + emits
#    per-row newline-delimited JSON to stdout, in two shapes.
#    SECURITY: the on-failure line's ``error`` field is populated
#    via ``str(exc)`` and MAY surface exception context that varies
#    per-logger: ``str(exc)`` typically shows only the codename + 1
#    offending byte (e.g. ``UnicodeDecodeError`` returns ``'<enc>'
#    codec can't decode byte 0xNN in position N`` ; ``InvalidToken``
#    returns a literal ``'Fernet token is invalid'`` with no
#    ciphertext echo). HOWEVER, broader log formatters using
#    ``repr(exc)``, exception ``__traceback__`` locals, or custom
#    ``__str__`` overrides CAN include additional bytes —
#    potentially the POST-Fernet-decrypt plaintext webhook secret.
#    Audit logs are therefore NOT
#    Audit logs are therefore NOT safe to ship unredacted to a
#    wide-access log-aggregator destination; redact the
#    ``error`` field downstream OR forward only to a sealed log
#    store. (In two shapes:)
#    success: ``{"subscription_id":"...","status":"rotated"}``;
#    failure: ``{"subscription_id":"...","status":"decrypt_failed","error":"<exc msg>"}``
#    (log-aggregator pipelines should key off ``subscription_id``
#    + ``status``; ``error`` is a freeform human-readability sidecar
#    on failures only) + a summary JSON line
#    to stderr (``{"status":"done","rotated_count":N,
#    "failed_count":M}``). Exits 1 if ``SECRETS_KEK_OLD ==
#    SECRETS_KEK`` — the no-op guard prevents accidental
#    re-encryption under the same key.)
# 5. After the migration completes successfully (``failed_count: 0``
#    in the summary line), remove ``SECRETS_KEK_OLD`` +
#    ``SECRETS_KEK_FALLBACK`` from ``.env`` to decommission the
#    OLD KEK. The OLD KEK MUST NOT remain in the fallback list
#    indefinitely — chain one rotation at a time per the plan 015
#    maintenance note.
# 6. PARTIAL-FAILURE rollback: if ``failed_count > 0`` (some rows
#    could not be decrypted under ``SECRETS_KEK_OLD`` — e.g. a
#    manually-edited row or a KEK mismatch deeper in history), DO
#    NOT decommission ``SECRETS_KEK_OLD`` / ``SECRETS_KEK_FALLBACK``
#    yet — the read-path still needs the OLD KEK for those unmigrated
#    rows. DO NOT RE-RUN the script — it is NOT idempotent; on a
#    second run, ``old_fernet.decrypt()`` would re-raise
#    ``FernetInvalidToken`` for every row already encrypted under the
#    new KEK (the ``rollback()`` in the except block leaves the row
#    UNCHANGED but ``failed_count`` would balloon, falsely signalling
#    a failed migration). Instead, investigate each ``decrypt_failed``
#    row by-hand and either delete it or recover the plaintext through
#    another channel (e.g. the prior secrets manager that originally
#    provisioned the subscription) before re-encrypting under the new
#    KEK with a small one-off helper. Once ``failed_count: 0`` from
#    the migrated-row count, THEN decommission. A mixed-state
#    database is NOT a deployment failure; decommissioning#    prematurely is. RECOVERY-path on a partial failure (after the
#    ``failed_count > 0`` summary lands): triage each ``decrypt_failed``
#    row via
#      psql -c "SELECT id, ciphertext FROM webhook_subscriptions WHERE id = '…'"
#    to disambiguate ALREADY-MIGRATED (the row's ciphertext is now
#    under the NEW KEK — the row IS correctly rotated; the
#    ``audit_line {"status":"rotated"}`` from the first run is the
#    source of truth; the false-negative on re-run is harmless)
#    vs. GENUINELY-CORRUPT (manual edit or KEK-mismatch deeper in
#    history — the row must be deleted + recreated with a fresh
#    secret; the original plaintext is unrecoverable without the
#    original provisioning-time secrets manager). DO NOT normalise
#    a partial migration by re-running the CLI.

SECRETS_KEK=

# v0.10.1 plan 010: Arq parser worker (replaces BackgroundTasks).
# The Arq broker is the Redis instance declared in docker-compose.yml.
# Both the FastAPI app's lifespan (initialises the enqueue pool) and
# the Arq worker process (dequeues ``parse_job``) read these at
# import time. Defaults (``localhost`` + 6379) match the local
# ``docker compose up -d redis`` dev setup; override here for a
# remote broker in staging/production.
# ARQ_REDIS_HOST=localhost
# ARQ_REDIS_PORT=6379

# v0.10.1 plan 010: in-request parse fallback (escape hatch for
# production safety + test env). When UNSET (default, production
# recommended), a misconfigured Arq broker surfaces as ``503 Service
# Unavailable`` on POST /api/v1/uploads (the operator sees the
# misconfiguration via HTTP 5xx in their dashboard + WARNING logs).
# When SET to ``1``, the route handler falls back to running the
# parse + dispatch in-request via ``asyncio.to_thread`` (graceful
# degradation: the API still serves traffic, but uploads become
# GIL-bound and slow at high concurrency -- bug #2 mitigation is
# NOT active in this path). Test env sets this to ``1`` via the
# ``_disable_arq_for_tests`` conftest fixture.
# ALLOW_INREQUEST_PARSE_FALLBACK=

# v0.10.12 plan 014: stuck-upload sweeper (worker crash recovery).
# Marks uploads stuck in `pending` for > STUCK_SWEEPER_THRESHOLD_S
# as `failed` every STUCK_SWEEPER_INTERVAL_S. Tune for large
# .zevtc files (5min default is conservative; bump to 1800s if
# your largest parses take 10+ min).
# STUCK_SWEEPER_INTERVAL_S=300
# STUCK_SWEEPER_THRESHOLD_S=300
